          <div class="row justify-content-center text-center">
            <div class="col-xl-8 col-lg-9 col-md-10">
              <h1 class="pb-3">Soil Sampling Instructions</h1>
              <p class="text-muted mb-0 fs-lg">Accurate lab results start with properly collected samples. Follow these instructions to ensure your soil samples provide reliable, actionable data for your project.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>  
      </div>

      <!-- Main Content -->
      <section class="container py-5">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-lg-10 offset-lg-1">

            <!-- Before You Start -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-calendar-check text-primary me-2"></i>Before You Start</h2>
              
              <h3 class="h5">When to Sample</h3>
              <ul class="mb-4">
                <li><strong>Best time:</strong> Sample before applying fertilizer, lime, or other amendments so you get a baseline reading.</li>
                <li><strong>Avoid sampling:</strong> Immediately after heavy rain or irrigation—wait 1–2 days for soil to drain to field capacity.</li>
                <li><strong>Consistency:</strong> If you sample the same area annually, try to sample at the same time of year for comparable results.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3 class="h5">Choose the Right Test</h3>
              <p>Your test goals affect how you collect, store, and transport samples:</p>
              <div class="table-responsive mb-4">
                <table class="table table-bordered sampling-table">
                  <thead class="table-light">
                    <tr>
                      <th>Test Type</th>
                      <th>Container</th>
                      <th>Handling Notes</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td><strong>Routine Fertility</strong><br>(pH, nutrients, organic matter)</td>
                      <td>Zip bag or plastic jar</td>
                      <td>No special handling; avoid heat</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td><strong>Metals Testing</strong></td>
                      <td>Clean plastic container</td>
                      <td>Avoid metal tools/containers</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td><strong>Pesticides / Organic Compounds</strong></td>
                      <td>Glass jar with tight lid</td>
                      <td>Contact lab first—requirements vary</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td><strong>Microbiology</strong></td>
                      <td>Sterile container</td>
                      <td>Keep cool (ice packs); deliver within 24–48 hours</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <div class="callout callout-important">
                <div class="callout-title"><i class="bx bx-info-circle me-1"></i>Important</div>
                If you're unsure which test you need or have special requirements, contact us <strong>before</strong> you collect samples. We can advise on containers, volumes, and handling.
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- What You Need -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-list-check text-primary me-2"></i>What You Need</h2>
              <p><strong>Gather these supplies before heading to the field:</strong></p>
              <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <ul class="list-unstyled">
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-check text-success me-2"></i>Clean <strong>plastic bucket</strong> (not galvanized metal)</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-check text-success me-2"></i>Clean plastic or stainless steel trowel/scoop</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-check text-success me-2"></i>Soil probe or auger (optional but helpful)</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-check text-success me-2"></i>Disposable gloves</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <ul class="list-unstyled">
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-check text-success me-2"></i>Sealable plastic bags or containers</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-check text-success me-2"></i>Permanent marker and labels</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-check text-success me-2"></i>Chain of Custody form (<a href="/forms.html">download here</a>)</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-check text-success me-2"></i>Cooler with ice packs (for microbiology samples)</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="callout callout-tip mt-3">
                <div class="callout-title"><i class="bx bx-bulb me-1"></i>Pro Tip</div>
                Rinse your bucket and tools with distilled water between sampling different areas to prevent cross-contamination. Avoid tools with rust, fertilizer residue, or contact with treated wood.
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Where to Sample -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-map text-primary me-2"></i>Where to Sample</h2>
              
              <h3 class="h5">Define Your Sampling Areas</h3>
              <p>Divide your property into zones based on:</p>
              <ul class="mb-4">
                <li>Visible differences in soil color, texture, or drainage</li>
                <li>Different uses (lawn vs. vegetable garden vs. orchard)</li>
                <li>Slope or elevation changes</li>
                <li>Areas with known problems (poor growth, salt buildup, etc.)</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="row mb-4">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card border-0 shadow-sm h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h4 class="h6 text-primary">Routine Fertility Testing</h4>
                      <p class="mb-0">Collect a <strong>composite sample</strong> from each uniform area. This combines multiple subsamples into one representative sample.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 mt-3 mt-md-0">
                  <div class="card border-0 shadow-sm h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h4 class="h6 text-primary">Diagnostic / Problem Areas</h4>
                      <p class="mb-0">Sample the problem area and a nearby healthy area <strong>separately</strong>. Label them clearly (e.g., "Dead patch" vs. "Healthy lawn"). This helps identify what's different.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- How to Collect -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-wrench text-primary me-2"></i>How to Collect the Sample</h2>
              
              <ol class="mb-4">
                <li class="mb-3">
                  <strong>Clear surface debris</strong><br>
                  Remove mulch, leaves, thatch, or grass clippings from the surface. You want to sample actual soil, not organic debris.
                </li>
                <li class="mb-3">
                  <strong>Determine sampling depth</strong><br>
                  Use the appropriate depth for your situation:
                  <div class="table-responsive mt-2">
                    <table class="table table-bordered table-sm sampling-table">
                      <thead class="table-light">
                        <tr>
                          <th>Application</th>
                          <th>Recommended Depth</th>
                        </tr>
                      </thead>
                      <tbody>
                        <tr>
                          <td>Lawns / Turf</td>
                          <td>0–4 inches (0–10 cm)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td>Gardens / Landscaping</td>
                          <td>0–6 inches (0–15 cm)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td>Trees / Shrub Root Zone</td>
                          <td>0–12 inches (0–30 cm) if requested</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                          <td>Agriculture (Row Crops)</td>
                          <td>0–6 or 0–12 inches—confirm with your agronomist or tell us your crop</td>
                        </tr>
                      </tbody>
                    </table>
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li class="mb-3">
                  <strong>Collect subsamples</strong><br>
                  Walk a random or zigzag pattern across your sampling area and collect soil cores or scoops:
                  <ul class="mt-2">
                    <li><strong>Small yard or garden bed:</strong> 5–10 subsamples</li>
                    <li><strong>Larger uniform areas (up to 5 acres):</strong> 10–20 subsamples</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li class="mb-3">
                  <strong>Mix thoroughly</strong><br>
                  Place all subsamples in your clean plastic bucket. Mix well with a trowel. Remove stones, roots, and debris.
                </li>
                <li class="mb-3">
                  <strong>Take the final sample</strong><br>
                  From the mixed soil, take the required amount and place it in your sample container.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <div class="callout callout-tip">
                <div class="callout-title"><i class="bx bx-bulb me-1"></i>Pro Tip</div>
                Avoid sampling near roads, compost piles, fence lines, old burn sites, or areas with recent chemical spills. These spots aren't representative of your main growing area.
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- How Much Soil -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-package text-primary me-2"></i>How Much Soil to Submit</h2>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Standard amount:</strong> About <strong>2 cups</strong> (approximately 250–500 grams) per sample</li>
                <li><strong>Specialty analyses</strong> (e.g., nematodes, certain pesticides) may require more—contact us if unsure</li>
                <li><strong>Microbiology samples:</strong> Follow our specific instructions or call ahead</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- Containers and Handling -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-box text-primary me-2"></i>Containers and Special Handling</h2>
              <div class="table-responsive">
                <table class="table table-bordered sampling-table">
                  <thead class="table-light">
                    <tr>
                      <th>Analysis Type</th>
                      <th>Container</th>
                      <th>Special Instructions</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td>Routine chemistry (pH, EC, nutrients, organic matter)</td>
                      <td>Clean zip-lock bag or plastic jar</td>
                      <td>Keep cool; no special rush</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td>Metals (lead, arsenic, etc.)</td>
                      <td>Clean plastic container or bag</td>
                      <td>Do not use metal tools or containers</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td>Pesticides / VOCs / Organics</td>
                      <td>Clean glass jar with PTFE-lined lid</td>
                      <td><strong>Call us first</strong>—requirements vary by compound</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td>Microbiology (bacteria, fungi, nematodes)</td>
                      <td>Sterile container provided by lab</td>
                      <td>Keep cold (ice packs); deliver within 24–48 hours</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Labeling -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-label text-primary me-2"></i>Labeling Requirements</h2>
              <p>Every sample container must be clearly labeled with a permanent marker. Include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Your name or company</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Unique Sample ID</strong> (e.g., "FIELD-A-1", "Backyard-North")</li>
                <li><strong>Collection date</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Location/area description</strong> (e.g., "Front lawn near oak tree")</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="callout callout-important mt-4">
                <div class="callout-title"><i class="bx bx-info-circle me-1"></i>Important</div>
                Your sample labels <strong>must match</strong> the information on your Chain of Custody form exactly. Mismatched labels delay results.
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Packaging and Delivery -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-send text-primary me-2"></i>Packaging and Delivery</h2>
              
              <h3 class="h5">Preparing Your Samples</h3>
              <ul class="mb-4">
                <li>Seal all containers tightly to prevent leaks</li>
                <li>Double-bag samples in zip-lock bags for extra protection</li>
                <li>Place all samples in a single sturdy box or cooler</li>
                <li>Include your completed <a href="/forms.html">Chain of Custody form</a> inside the package</li>
              </ul>

              <h3 class="h5">Keeping Samples Cool</h3>
              <ul class="mb-4">
                <li>Store samples out of direct sunlight and heat</li>
                <li>Refrigerate if you can't deliver same-day</li>
                <li><strong>Microbiology samples:</strong> Pack with ice packs or frozen gel packs; deliver within 24–48 hours</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card border-0 shadow-sm h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h4 class="h6 text-primary"><i class="bx bx-buildings me-2"></i>Local Drop-Off</h4>
                      <p class="mb-0">Bring samples to our laboratory during normal business hours. No appointment needed for sample drop-off.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 mt-3 mt-md-0">
                  <div class="card border-0 shadow-sm h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h4 class="h6 text-primary"><i class="bx bx-package me-2"></i>Shipping</h4>
                      <p class="mb-0">Use a sturdy box with cushioning material. Ship early in the week to avoid weekend delays. For microbiology, use overnight shipping with ice packs.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Chain of Custody -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-file text-primary me-2"></i>Chain of Custody Form</h2>
              <p>A completed Chain of Custody (COC) form is <strong>required</strong> with every submission. The COC:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Documents who collected the samples and when</li>
                <li>Lists all samples and requested analyses</li>
                <li>Provides your contact information for results delivery</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="d-flex flex-wrap gap-3 mt-4">
                <a href="/forms.html" class="btn btn-primary">
                  <i class="bx bx-download me-2"></i>Download Chain of Custody Form
                </a>
                <a href="mailto:motzz@motzzlaboratory.com" class="btn btn-outline-primary">
                  <i class="bx bx-envelope me-2"></i>Contact Us for Sample Containers
                </a>
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Common Mistakes -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-error-circle text-primary me-2"></i>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
              <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <ul class="list-unstyled">
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-x text-danger me-2"></i>Mixing samples from different zones into one container</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-x text-danger me-2"></i>Sampling too shallow or too deep for your test goal</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-x text-danger me-2"></i>Using galvanized, rusty, or dirty containers/tools</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <ul class="list-unstyled">
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-x text-danger me-2"></i>Incomplete or unclear labels on sample containers</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-x text-danger me-2"></i>Leaving samples in a hot car for hours</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><i class="bx bx-x text-danger me-2"></i>Forgetting to include the Chain of Custody form</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mb-5">
              <h2 class="h3 mb-4"><i class="bx bx-question-mark text-primary me-2"></i>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
              
              <div class="accordion" id="soilFAQ">
                <div class="accordion-item">
                  <h3 class="accordion-header" id="faq1">
                    <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqAnswer1" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faqAnswer1">
                      Do I need to dry the soil before submitting?
                    </button>
                  </h3>
                  <div id="faqAnswer1" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="faq1" data-bs-parent="#soilFAQ">
                    <div class="accordion-body">
                      <strong>Generally no.</strong> Submit soil as-collected. Our lab will dry and process it appropriately. Do not oven-dry or microwave samples unless specifically instructed.
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="accordion-item">
                  <h3 class="accordion-header" id="faq2">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqAnswer2" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqAnswer2">
                      Can I submit wet or muddy soil?
                    </button>
                  </h3>
                  <div id="faqAnswer2" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="faq2" data-bs-parent="#soilFAQ">
                    <div class="accordion-body">
                      <strong>Yes</strong>, but avoid samples with standing water or saturated mud. Moist soil is fine. If soil is extremely wet, let it drain briefly (don't heat-dry it) and note "wet sample" on your label. Very wet samples may take longer to process.
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="accordion-item">
                  <h3 class="accordion-header" id="faq3">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqAnswer3" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqAnswer3">
                      How many samples do I need?
                    </button>
                  </h3>
                  <div id="faqAnswer3" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="faq3" data-bs-parent="#soilFAQ">
                    <div class="accordion-body">
                      <strong>One composite sample per uniform zone.</strong> A small residential property might need only 1–3 samples (front lawn, backyard, garden bed). Larger properties or farms typically need one sample per 2–5 acres of uniform soil. When in doubt, contact us.
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="accordion-item">
                  <h3 class="accordion-header" id="faq4">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#faqAnswer4" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faqAnswer4">
                      How long does testing take?
                    </button>
                  </h3>
